# Project: Tip Calculator
# Framework: Streamlit (Python)
# Python version: 3.11+

## Coding Standards
- Use Python 3.11+ features and syntax
- Use type hints for all function parameters and return values
- Add Google-style docstrings to all functions (Args, Returns, Raises sections)
- Use descriptive variable names (avoid single-letter names except for loop counters)
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helper functions when needed
- Never hardcode sample data — always connect to real variables or session state

## Streamlit Conventions
- Use st.set_page_config() at the top of the main app file
- Always validate user input before performing calculations
- Use st.error() for error messages, st.warning() for soft warnings, st.info() for neutral messages
- Use st.stop() after st.error() or st.warning() when the app cannot proceed
- Use st.cache_data for any expensive computations or data loading
- Never put primary results behind a button if they should be visible immediately

## Project Structure
- app.py: Main Streamlit application (UI only — no business logic)
- utils.py: All utility and calculation functions
- data/: Directory for any data files (CSV, JSON)

## Visualization
- Always use Plotly for charts, never Matplotlib
- Color palette: ["#1f77b4", "#ff7f0e", "#2ca02c", "#d62728"]
- Always include chart titles, X-axis labels, Y-axis labels, and hover tooltips
- Format currency tooltips as "$X.XX"
- Charts should be always visible when data exists — do not gate them behind buttons

## What NOT to do
- Do not import numpy or matplotlib — they are not in requirements.txt
- Do not hardcode test values in production code
- Do not use st.write() for user-facing messages — use st.metric(), st.error(), st.info() etc.
- Do not put API keys or secrets in any file
